recommending a plan. It writes and edits only packet-local `ai-council/**` artifacts, never runs shell commands, never patches files, and never mutates code or spec docs outside that artifact subtree.\n\n  Line 29: **CRITICAL**: You MUST seek diversity in both reasoning lens and AI vantage point. Do not run the same strategy three ways. Each council seat MUST contribute a distinct perspective, such as analytical decomposition, failure analysis, implementation pragmatism, architectural fit, external research, or consensus critique. Output is a plan plus packet-local `ai-council/**` artifacts. NEVER write outside `ai-council/**`.\n\n  Line 37: Single-round council behavior remains the default for this agent. Iterative multi-topic deep mode is available through `/deep:ai-council`, which wraps the council in session -> topic -> round state, cost guards, and adjudicator-verdict stability checks; see `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/SKILL.md` Section \"Deep Mode (Iterative Multi-Topic)\".\n\n  Line 43: **Semantic:** the deep-ai-council threshold scores per-topic Round-N -> Round-N+1 verdict deltas from the adjudicator. Lower = more rounds / higher stability threshold.\n\n  Line 75: 0. **RESOLVE** -> Determine the target packet path BEFORE any seat dispatch. Persistence under `<packet>/ai-council/**` is mandatory; the packet path must be known before DIVERSIFY. Apply this resolution rule in order, stopping at the first match:\n\n  Line 79:    4. Else, HALT and ask the user a single, focused question: \"Which spec folder should I persist `ai-council/` artifacts under?\" List the resolution candidates you tried in (1)-(3). Do NOT dispatch council seats. Do NOT emit a chat-form Council Report. Wait for the user to provide a packet path.\n\n  Line 93: 8. **DELIVER** -> Present the Multi-AI Council Report with council composition, comparison table, deliberation notes, implementation roadmap, confidence score, and persisted `ai-council/**` artifacts. Do not apply code or spec changes outside the council artifact subtree.\n\n  Line 134: > **Scoped-write permissions**: This agent has read/search access for analysis and may write/edit only packet-local `ai-council/**` artifacts.\n\n  Line 135: > Bash and Patch remain denied. Any write outside `ai-council/**` is an `OUT_OF_SCOPE_WRITE` violation.\n\n  Line 399: - **Persist `ai-council/**` artifacts directly via the `lib/persist-artifacts.cjs` named exports BEFORE claiming completion.** The minimum required artifact set is: `ai-council-config.json`, `ai-council-state.jsonl` (with at least `round_start` + `seat_returned` x N + `deliberation_synthesized` + `round_end` + `council_complete` events), `ai-council-strategy.md`, `seats/round-NNN/seat-MMM-*.md` for each dispatched seat, `deliberations/round-NNN.md`, and `council-report.md`.\n\n  Line 403: - Modify files outside `ai-council/**`. This is a scoped-write planning agent; code/spec implementation belongs to the user or another agent.\n\n  Line 404: - **Deliver a council report without persisting the canonical artifact set.** A chat-only response without `ai-council/**` artifacts on disk is an enforcement violation, not a successful run.\n\n  Line 406: - Use Bash or Patch tools, or write/edit outside `ai-council/**`. Bash and Patch stay denied; out-of-scope writes must fail with `OUT_OF_SCOPE_WRITE`.\n\n  Line 426: The canonical schema for §8 lives at `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/structure/output_schema.md` — both this section and the `persist-artifacts.cjs` helper cite it. Schema changes require lockstep update of all three.\n\n  Line 524: [] No file modifications attempted OUTSIDE `ai-council/**` (scoped-write only; writes to `<packet>/ai-council/**` are mandatory and tracked separately in PERSISTENCE VERIFICATION below)\n\n  Line 534: [] `<packet>/ai-council/` directory exists at the resolved target path.\n\n  Line 535: [] `ai-council-config.json` written via `writeConfig` with current_round and status.\n\n  Line 536: [] `ai-council-state.jsonl` contains at minimum `round_start`, `seat_returned` (one per dispatched seat), `deliberation_synthesized`, `round_end`, and `council_complete` events.\n\n  Line 537: [] `ai-council-strategy.md` written via `writeStrategyMd` with charter content.\n\n  Line 559: 10. Did I avoid file modifications outside `ai-council/**` (i.e., scoped-write only)? (YES/NO)\n\n  Line 560: 11. Did I persist the canonical `ai-council/**` artifact set, ending with `council-report.md` and a `council_complete` state event? (YES/NO)\n\n  Line 563: Fix verification gaps first. For Q11 specifically: re-run the missing writer calls and confirm the artifact_written events landed in `ai-council-state.jsonl` before delivering.\n\n  Line 615: | **Out-of-scope File Modification** | Council write authority is limited to `ai-council/**` | Persist council artifacts only. User or another agent executes code/spec changes |\n\n  Line 624: ## 12. OUTPUT PROTOCOL - `ai-council/` SUBFOLDER CONVENTION\n\n  Line 626: Persist council artifacts under `<packet>/ai-council/` where `<packet>` is the path resolved at §1 Step 0 RESOLVE. Persistence is mandatory on every council run; the prior conditional language (\"when invoked with a spec_folder\") was removed because Step 0 ensures the packet path is always available before DELIVER. If Step 0 cannot resolve a packet path and the user is not present to answer the HALT-and-ASK question, the council does NOT run — the layout below is therefore guaranteed to apply to every completed deliberation. Layout parity with `research/` from deep-research and `review/` from deep-review. Chat output may summarize the result, but the packet artifact is the source of truth for rounds, seats, critique, resume, and final plan.\n\n  Line 629: specs/<track>/<NNN-name>/ai-council/\n\n  Line 630: |-- ai-council-config.json     (one per packet, mutated across runs)\n\n  Line 631: |-- ai-council-strategy.md     (charter authored on first run)\n\n  Line 632: |-- ai-council-state.jsonl     (append-only state log)\n\n  Line 640: - `ai-council-config.json`: `{spec_folder, current_round, max_rounds, seats_per_round, convergence_signal, created_at, updated_at, status}`. Mutate across runs; do not duplicate.\n\n  Line 641: - `ai-council-strategy.md`: charter with purpose, task framing, selected lenses, executor/vantage targets, evidence inputs, convergence rule, and known constraints.\n\n  Line 642: - `ai-council-state.jsonl`: append-only events: `round_start`, `seat_returned`, `deliberation_synthesized`, `round_end`, `council_complete`, plus v1.2 `artifact_written`, `rollback`, and `artifact_superseded`.\n\n  Line 648: Reference: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/structure/folder_layout.md`.\n\n  Line 654: 1. **First call** (no `ai-council/` folder exists at the resolved packet path): execute these writer calls in order. Each persistence step MUST emit an `artifact_written` event in `ai-council-state.jsonl` before the next step begins. Treat any skipped step as a §9 Q11 violation.\n\n  Line 655:    1. `writeConfig(...)` -> initialize `ai-council-config.json` with `current_round: 1`, `status: \"in_progress\"`, and timestamps. (emit `artifact_written`)\n\n  Line 665: 2. **Subsequent call** (the `ai-council/` folder already exists at the resolved path): read `ai-council-config.json` and `ai-council-state.jsonl`. Determine the next round from `(highest round_end event).round + 1`. Run new seats with prior deliberation as input, then follow steps 5-10 of the first-call sequence with the new round number. Append state events; do not rewrite history.\n\n  Line 668: Reference: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/structure/state_format.md`.\n\n  Line 695: `ai-council-state.jsonl` is append-only. NEVER rewrite or truncate it. NEVER write secrets, credentials, tokens, or private keys to state events.\n\n  Line 699: Writer-emitted rows may prefix each event with `schema_version`, `protocol`, and `producer`. Missing `schema_version` means implicit `\"1\"`; v1.2 writers emit `\"1.2\"`, `protocol:\"ai-council\"`, and `producer:\"persist-artifacts@1.2.0\"`.\n\n  Line 701: Evolution is additive-only: v1 callers must keep working, and old rows are not rewritten. Full state-format rules live in `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/structure/state_format.md`.\n\n  Line 720: The council writes packet artifacts directly through `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/lib/persist-artifacts.cjs`. Use the named exports in order as each round closes: `writeStateJsonl`, `writeConfig`, `writeStrategyMd`, `writeSeat`, `writeDeliberation`, `writeCritique`, and `writeReport`. Each writer resolves the target under `<packet>/ai-council/`, writes the artifact, then appends an `artifact_written` event with byte count and sha256 checksum to `ai-council-state.jsonl`.\n\n  Line 724: 1. **Allowed root**: `<packet>/ai-council/**` only.\n\n  Line 726: 3. **Out-of-scope writes**: any target outside `ai-council/**` must fail with `OUT_OF_SCOPE_WRITE` before touching the filesystem.\n\n  Line 727: 4. **Helper fallback**: non-council callers may still invoke `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/persist-artifacts.cjs`. The helper is now a thin CLI wrapper around the same library exports.\n\n  Line 729: Depth-1 rule: the LEAF council owns writes to `ai-council/**` directly. The dispatching parent owns code/spec implementation after the council returns, but it does not need to invoke the helper for normal council artifact persistence.\n\n  Line 738: node .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/persist-artifacts.cjs <packet> \\\n\n  Line 746: The payload routes through existing decision-record, implementation-summary, and handover categories. No new ANCHOR family is introduced. See `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/patterns/command_wiring.md`.\n\n  Line 752: Round rollback is scoped to one `round-NNN` unit. If a seat errors, times out below the minimum quorum, or convergence fails after the configured maximum, write a `rollback` event to `ai-council-state.jsonl`, move the round artifacts into `ai-council/failed/round-NNN-<timestamp>/`, and append `artifact_superseded` markers for every `artifact_written` event from that round.\n\n  Line 756: 1. Inspect `ai-council/failed/round-NNN-<timestamp>/` for forensic context.\n\n  Line 776: │  └─► Output plan plus scoped ai-council artifacts                         │\n\n  Line 786: │  └─► 8. DELIVER     Report + ai-council artifacts                         │\n\n  Line 795: │  ├─► Writes/edits only within ai-council/**                              │\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-sk-prompt-models-rename/004-commands-scripts-data/implementation-summary.md:\n  Line 47: Repointed the `/deep:model-benchmark` + `/deep:context` workflow YAMLs (benchmark output/promote/prompt-framing paths), `model-benchmark.md`, the pre-commit hook, the deep-context agent, and the repo-root `README.md` at `sk-prompt-models`. Also caught the cross-runtime mirrors outside `.opencode/`: `.claude/agents/deep-context.md`, `.codex/agents/deep-context.toml`, `.github/workflows/prompt-card-sync.yml` (CI guard), and `AGENTS.md`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.claude/agents/deep-research.md:\n  Line 38: - `deep-ai-council` uses 0.20 default on adjudicator-verdict stability\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep.md:\n  Line 43: | `ai-council` | `council` | `/deep:ai-council` | `deep-ai-council` | `@ai-council` | `ai-council/` |\n\n  Line 45: `ai-council` is `mode: subagent` (Task-dispatch only, no direct top-level invocation) like the other three modes; this router reaches it the same way it reaches `context`/`research`/`review`.\n\n  Line 53: 1. **Do not absorb a leaf role.** If the request resolves to `research`, `review`, `context`, or `ai-council`, route to the selected agent; do not perform the leaf's iteration/review/context/council work yourself.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-context.md:\n  Line 4: mode: subagent\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-review.md:\n  Line 4: mode: subagent\n\n  Line 48: - `deep-ai-council` uses 0.20 default on adjudicator-verdict stability\n\n  Line 294: | `.codex/agents/deep-review.toml` | Mirror of canonical agent | Read-only context if explicitly in review scope; never edit |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.claude/agents/ai-council.md:\n  Line 2: name: ai-council\n\n  Line 3: description: \"AI Council scoped-write planning architect: diverse AI lenses, multi-round deliberation, ai-council artifact writes only.\"\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"deep-route-guard|mk-deep-loop-guard|ai-council|mode: all|mode: subagent|\\.toml mirror|agents/.*toml","time":{"start":1782919041529,"end":1782919041569}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_052b73d6d7448eb4016a452f7fafbc8191beea6da064d6e2c7"}},"id":"prt_f1e4191f2001X69hbZsHIBVxnI","sessionID":"ses_0e1c12f14ffe56Cs01FOXHPL99","messageID":"msg_f1e412e42001e7STSMZLmXs9fI"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782919041584,"sessionID":"ses_0e1c12f14ffe56Cs01FOXHPL99","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_umIJTnJUbF1Zc1nAQsRIcpyv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\\.opencode/agents/\\*\\.toml|agents/.*toml|mirror|mirrors","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/frontmatter_templates.md:\n  Line 358: | `title` | Plain string | Non-empty; usually mirrors the H1 |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md:\n  Line 3: First major iteration of `sk-doc` after the v1.3.0.0 series. Packet 102 ships five sequential phases that restructure the skill surface: reference relocation, a dedicated skill README asset, an agent identity rename across three runtime mirrors, manual playbook coverage for the renamed agent, and a single transactional remediation pass that closes every P1 and P2 finding from the phase-parent deep-review. All five phases land as additive child packets in `skilled-agent-orchestration/102-sk-doc-skill-readme-and-structure`. The `/create:*` command family stays surface-stable.\n\n  Line 25: The dedicated documentation executor agent renames from `@create` to `@markdown` across all three runtime mirrors: `.opencode/agents/markdown.md`, `.claude/agents/markdown.md`, and `.codex/agents/markdown.toml`. The Codex registry block updates from `[agents.create]` to `[agents.markdown]` with `config_file = \"agents/markdown.toml\"`. Orchestrator and code-agent references route documentation and component authoring through `@markdown`. The `/create:*` command family (`/create:agent`, `/create:sk-skill`, `/create:feature-catalog`, `/create:testing-playbook`, `/create:folder_readme`, `/create:changelog`) keeps every invocation unchanged because this is an agent identity rename, not a command-family rename.\n\n  Line 57: The rename decouples agent identity (`@markdown`) from command-family identity (`/create:*`). Before this phase the two were conflated, so renaming the agent risked breaking command callers. The decoupling lets the documentation executor evolve under one name while every `/create:*` invocation keeps working. The Codex TOML mirror needed the same identity rename because `.codex/agents/create.toml` existed and was wired through `[agents.create]` in `.codex/config.toml`.\n\n  Line 63: The cli-codex `@markdown` typed-agent dispatch gap reflects a two-registry architecture in codex v0.130.0. The `.codex/config.toml` user-defined agent block IS read for CLI context, but the `codex_core::tools::router` SpawnAgent runtime allowlist is a separate baked-in list that does NOT propagate user-defined agents. The resolution rewrites SD-019 with `execution_mode: dispatch_inline_contract`, an explicit SpawnAgent forbid, a Gate 3 pre-answer of \"D) Skip\", a BINDING-trace requirement, and contract-acknowledgment fields in success criteria. Codex `gpt-5.5` then reads `.codex/agents/markdown.toml` developer_instructions and follows them itself without dispatching a sub-agent. SD-018 and SD-020 still verify real typed-agent dispatch, so the three CLIs test the same agent identity through three different mechanisms.\n\n  Line 74: | Old-identity grep across runtime mirrors and commands after Phase 003      | PASS, zero `@create` / `create.md` / `create.toml`  |\n\n  Line 75: | New-file presence test for the three runtime mirrors after Phase 003       | PASS, all three `markdown.*` files exist            |\n\n  Line 99: Downstream agents and orchestrators that previously typed `@create` as the documentation executor MUST switch to `@markdown`. The rename applies to all three runtime mirrors. Specifically:\n\n  Line 103: 3. Update any saved prompt or template that hard-coded `agents/create.md` or `agents/create.toml` paths.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook_snippet_template.md:\n  Line 24: Each feature file is the canonical home for full scenario execution detail. The root `manual_testing_playbook.md` stays readable by summarizing the feature and linking here, while the feature file carries the realistic user-testing context, orchestration process, 9-column test row, structured source references, and concise metadata. The file shape should intentionally mirror the Feature Catalog snippet pattern so operators can move between the catalog and the playbook without relearning the document structure.\n\n  Line 29: - Frontmatter that mirrors the larger root docs (`title` + `description`)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook_template.md:\n  Line 31: - **Feature-catalog shaped files**: Per-feature playbook files should mirror feature-catalog snippet structure by leading with prose, then current reality, then structured source references.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-claude-code/SKILL.md:\n  Line 354:    2. **Model override (mandatory for a profiled model).** If the target model has a profile at `../sk-prompt-models/references/models/<id>.md`, that profile OVERRIDES the cross-model default. The **sk-prompt-models** hub owns per-model prompt-craft (framework + scaffold + gotchas, mirroring `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json` `recommended_frameworks`); consult it before composing for any small model.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/benchmark/source_template.md:\n  Line 100: - An evidence file is added or fundamentally revised: mirror the change in §4.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:\n  Line 42: - Composing GitHub release notes that mirror the changelog body\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/feature_catalog/feature_catalog_snippet_template.md:\n  Line 54: - `title` and `description` should mirror the root catalog entry for this feature (same wording, same scope)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-claude-code/changelog/v1.1.6.0.md:\n  Line 4: **Status**: Documentation-only addendum. RCAF default in `assets/prompt_quality_card.md` §3 was already present (mirrors `sk-prompt`'s general default). This patch adds the \"Pre-planning density\" composition-guidance note that complements RCAF.\n\n  Line 20: | `assets/prompt_quality_card.md` | Updated | §3 Task-to-framework map gains a \"Pre-planning density\" note after the table. RCAF default was already present (mirrors sk-prompt). |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/assets/README.md:\n  Line 24: - The asset schema mirrors the verification battery contract used by `gold-query-verifier.ts`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/mcp_server/tests/__fixtures__/README.md:\n  Line 22: - `index-scope.ts` mirrors scan-scope policy in a compact fixture form for indexer tests.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md:\n  Line 324:    2. **Model override (mandatory for a profiled model).** If the target model has a profile at `../sk-prompt-models/references/models/<id>.md`, that profile OVERRIDES the cross-model default. The **sk-prompt-models** hub owns per-model prompt-craft (framework + scaffold + gotchas, mirroring `sk-prompt-models/assets/model_profiles.json` `recommended_frameworks`); consult it before composing for any small model.\n\n  Line 418: - Self-invocation guard pseudocode reproduced in Section 2 mirrors ADR-001.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 67: - **SD-019** — `06--agent-dispatch/markdown-agent-cli-opencode.md` — `@markdown` agent inline-contract execution via cli-opencode (gpt-5.5/xhigh/fast). Verifies opencode follows `.opencode/agents/markdown.toml` developer_instructions itself (no SpawnAgent) because the SpawnAgent runtime allowlist upstream-blocks user-defined agents — rubric differs from SD-018/020; see scenario header.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/changelog/v1.0.3.0.md:\n  Line 67: - 29 stale `.d.ts` files deleted at source level (mirrors the .js cleanup; zero external consumers confirmed via grep).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/changelog/v1.3.0.0.md:\n  Line 31: BEFORE: even once the writer worked, `asOfEdgesFrom` had no production caller, so the preserved history was dead. AFTER: `code_graph_query` takes an optional `asOf` generation parameter that routes edge reads through `asOfEdgesFrom` and a new `asOfEdgesTo` inbound mirror, skipping the dangling-edge exclusion because a historical edge legitimately points at a now-deleted node. An as-of query at a past generation returns the old target while the default query returns the new.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/manual_testing_playbook/04--context-retrieval/code-graph-context-readiness-block.md:\n  Line 49: Call with a single stale file and verify selective self-heal mirrors query behavior.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:\n  Line 25: **Feature-to-tool granularity (F013/F014).** The 14 runtime features (excluding the CLI fallback surface, which mirrors the whole tool set) map to **8 MCP tools** in the `mk-code-index` server because individual features often compose multiple operations on the same tool. For example, `code_graph_query` provides multiple query operations (`outline`, `calls_from`, `calls_to`, `imports_from`, `imports_to`, `blast_radius`), each catalogued as its own feature. Previously, the **coverage-graph deep-loop tools** (`deep_loop_graph_*`) were registered with the `mk-spec-memory` MCP server; they were removed in arc 118 (FULL_ISOLATE_NO_MCP) and now live as direct `.cjs` script entry points under `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/scripts/`. The catalog entries below are retained as historical reference and point at the current script paths.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/context-budget.md:\n  Line 6:   - \"cli-opencode budget mirror\"\n\n  Line 28: Consult this mirror when composing a bounded cli-opencode prompt and you need the cli-opencode-specific model windows; for budget allocation, summary thresholds, truncation markers, and eviction order, read `../../sk-prompt-models/references/context_budget.md` and the shared defaults in `../../sk-prompt-models/assets/per_model_budgets.json`.\n\n  Line 32: The budget pattern stays canonical in sk-prompt-models; cli-opencode mirrors the semantics so callers compose bounded prompts without a second implementation or a drift-prone ruleset.\n\n  Line 38: Prompt packs hit the same failure mode when tool output, conversation history, and working memory exceed the selected model window. The pattern remains canonical in `../../sk-prompt-models/references/context_budget.md`; cli-opencode mirrors the semantics so callers can compose bounded prompts without adding a second implementation or drift-prone ruleset.\n\n  Line 40: This mirror is documentation-only. It does not add runtime budget logic or mutate memory state.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/references/runtime/naming_conventions.md:\n  Line 50: | MCP server name | `mk-code-index` | `opencode.json` `mcp.mk_code_index.*` and 5 runtime mirrors | Stable tool contract per ADR-002. Renaming would break every config that registers the server. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.14.0.md:\n  Line 12: 1. **Xiaomi Direct API** — The `xiaomi` provider is now documented as a pay-per-token alternative to `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan), mirroring how MiniMax has both `minimax-coding-plan` (Token Plan) and `minimax` (Direct API). Model: `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro`. Auth: `opencode providers login xiaomi`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/manual_testing_playbook/02--external-dispatch/self-invocation-refusal.md:\n  Line 30: - Expected execution process: External-AI orchestrator (or shell operator) exports `OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR` to simulate being inside OpenCode, then either calls a stand-in router script that mirrors the SKILL.md §2 self-invocation guard logic OR documents the expected refusal behavior of the skill if the dispatch were attempted from a real in-OpenCode session. The validation is that the documented refusal logic exists and is reachable.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.2.0.md:\n  Line 4: **Status**: Documentation-only addendum. RCAF default in `assets/prompt_quality_card.md` §3 was already present (mirrors `sk-prompt`'s general default). This patch adds the \"Pre-planning density\" composition-guidance note that complements RCAF.\n\n  Line 20: | `assets/prompt_quality_card.md` | Updated | §3 Task-to-framework map gains a \"Pre-planning density\" note after the table. RCAF default was already present (mirrors sk-prompt). |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.5.0.md:\n  Line 10: A live probe on opencode 1.15.13 (2026-06-01) confirmed the Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) provider `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` is configured and responsive: a one-shot dispatch to `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` returned cleanly with **no** `--agent` flag. This release wires MiMo-V2.5-Pro into the skill's registry and prompt assets so the model becomes an explicitly-selectable target, mirroring how MiniMax (`minimax-coding-plan`) is already wired.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/changelog/v1.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 25: | `.agents/commands/create/prompt.toml` | Modified | Fixed stale refs, added Step 1a interactive behavior |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md:\n  Line 13: Six files were `references/` but are really checklist artifacts a reviewer applies, not doctrine a reviewer reads: `code_quality_checklist.md`, `security_checklist.md`, `solid_checklist.md`, `test_quality_checklist.md`, `fix-completeness-checklist.md`, and `removal_plan.md`. They moved to a new `assets/` folder. The four genuine references stayed in `references/`: `review_core.md` (doctrine), `review_ux_single_pass.md` (single-pass UX behavior), `quick_reference.md` (index), and `pr_state_dedup.md` (the M-1 dedup spec). Every by-path reference was updated in lockstep — the §2 routing tables and `RESOURCE_MAP`, the README table, `graph-metadata.json`, the bidirectional sibling cross-links, nineteen manual-testing per-feature files, and the two cross-skill `sk-code/references/opencode/{python,shell}/quality_standards.md` pointers. The `.claude` and `.codex` runtime mirrors were re-synced. The rule canary keys on `pr_state_dedup.md` (which stayed), so it remains green.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/SKILL.md:\n  Line 279: The native `@deep-context` seat is dispatched **by name** (`agent: deep-context` in the loop YAML), resolved by each host runtime from its OWN `agents/` directory. It therefore lives as one canonical source plus two runtime mirrors that must stay in sync:\n\n  Line 284: | Claude Code | `.claude/agents/deep-context.md` | mirror — `tools:` allow-list (read-only), same body |\n\n  Line 285: | OpenCode | `.opencode/agents/deep-context.toml` | mirror — `developer_instructions = '''…'''` + `# Converted from:` header + `sandbox_mode = \"read-only\"`, same body |\n\n  Line 287: The body is identical across all three; only the frontmatter format differs. The command and loop YAML are **shared** — the `.claude/` and `.opencode/` `commands`/`prompts`/`skills` directories are symlinks to `.opencode/` — so they intentionally reference the canonical `.opencode/` paths and dispatch by name; do NOT fork them per runtime. If a mirror is missing for a runtime, the native seats silently fail to dispatch there (the CLI seats still run, but the cross-executor agreement signal degrades). When you edit the canonical agent, re-sync both mirrors in the same change.\n\n  Line 302: 8. **Keep the native agent's runtime mirrors in sync** — when editing `.opencode/agents/deep-context.md` (canonical), update `.claude/agents/deep-context.md` and `.opencode/agents/deep-context.toml` in the same change. The loop dispatches the native seat by name from each runtime's own `agents/` dir, so a missing mirror means native seats silently fail to dispatch in that runtime. See **Runtime Mirrors** in §3.\n\n  Line 435: Related skills: `deep-research` for outward/web investigation (sibling loop whose structure this mirrors), `deep-review` for code audit, `deep-loop-runtime` for shared executor and coverage-graph infrastructure, `sk-prompt-models` for per-model prompt framing, and `system-spec-kit` when packet documentation or memory continuity applies.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/INSTALL_GUIDE.md:\n  Line 355: The mk-spec-memory `embedder_set` / `embedder_status` MCP tools are intentionally NOT mirrored here. Skill-advisor's surface is one database helper plus the cascade-driven sentinel. Operator discipline owns any manual swap workflow; there is no async re-index orchestrator on the skill-advisor side.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/benchmark_creation.md:\n  Line 299: **What triggered adoption anyway**: the bake-off shape mirrored the sibling skill's text-embedder run, and the same operators move between the two skills. Symmetry across sibling MCP servers is itself an adoption trigger.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 35: > **Numbering note (gap-09).** The directory layout skips slot `09--*` between `08--scorer-fusion` and `10--python-compat`. This mirrors the `feature_catalog/` 05-gap pattern and is an intentional historical reservation from initial scaffold design. The gap is preserved to keep spec-folder cross-reference stability across packets. Do not renumber.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/SKILL.md:\n  Line 20: - OpenCode runtime: `.opencode/agents/*.toml`\n\n  Line 439: Cross-skill alignment: `deep-research` owns iterative investigation. Its shared resource family mirrors `deep-review` and `deep-ai-council`, but its vocabulary remains novelty, sources, negative knowledge, question coverage, and research synthesis rather than severity findings or council agreement.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/manual_testing_playbook/10--python-compat/stdin-mode.md:\n  Line 54: | Shim reads argv instead of stdin | Output mirrors argv prompt | Inspect `--stdin` parser. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/SKILL.md:\n  Line 125: - `feature_catalog/` mirrors the playbook 1:1 with one user-facing feature entry per scenario (32 entries) — start here for \"what does DAC-NNN actually do\" lookups.\n\n  Line 432: - ✅ Runtime mirrors dispatch `@ai-council` as the primary agent identity — the three agent files (`.opencode/agents/ai-council.md`, `.claude/agents/ai-council.md`, `.opencode/agents/ai-council.toml`) all declare `name: ai-council`, matching the registry `agent: ai-council` field.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 793: - `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/tests/deep-research-contract-parity.vitest.ts`: runtime mirror alignment, capability matrix coverage, and artifact naming.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/runtime/daemon_lease_contract.md:\n  Line 143: The launcher keeps `process.on('exit', clearLeaseFile)` as a normal-exit backstop, but signal mirroring cannot rely on it. If a child exits due to `SIGKILL`, Node cannot run parent `exit` handlers after `process.kill(process.pid, 'SIGKILL')`. The launcher therefore calls `clearLeaseFile()` synchronously before mirroring any child exit signal, and parent signal handlers clear the lease before exiting after the 5s SIGKILL backstop.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-figma/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 11: This release promotes the skill to a stable 1.0.0.0 line. Live external verification is complete: the real `figma-ds-cli` (1.2.0 full repo build) was installed and exercised, and an embedded install scaffold now mirrors the other mcp-server skills.\n\n  Line 19: - Added `mcp-servers/figma-cli/` as the canonical install entry point for the silships `figma-ds-cli`, mirroring the embedded-server layout used by `mcp-click-up`. `mcp-servers/figma-cli/setup.sh` delegates to the skill's canonical `scripts/install.sh`, which selects the full silships repo build over the minimal npm build and never installs the unrelated `figma-cli` npm package (unic/figma-cli, bin `figma`).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 167: Verify runtime mirrors expose `deep-ai-council` and active mirror paths do not retain `ai-council` as the primary identity.\n\n  Line 411: | Operator A/B comparison (with-graph vs no-graph baseline) | Operator-runnable contract mirrors the automated DAC-027..DAC-032 fixtures |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/05--pause-resume-and-fault-tolerance/pause-sentinel-halts-between-iterations.md:\n  Line 58: Use the loop protocol pause subsection as the canonical flow and verify both research and review YAMLs mirror it exactly.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/changelog/v0.4.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release repurposes `mcp_server/scripts/check-prompt-quality-card-sync.sh` from a 3-mirror hash-comparison sync checker into a focused duplication guard covering all 4 `cli-*` prompt-quality cards. The script now asserts that the canonical framework table and the CLEAR scoring table are not inlined in any per-CLI card; it exits 0 only when none of the four cards contain either table. The old hash-comparison logic is gone.\n\n  Line 9: The original script compared MD5 hashes across three mirror paths to detect divergence between the canonical prompt-quality card and its copies. That design required maintaining synchronized copies and a known-good hash baseline, and it fired false positives whenever a deliberate update had not yet propagated to all mirrors.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 394: Confirm the v3 Style Reference mirrors a11y-extract.ts output faithfully, never inventing values. In the v3 schema, captured accessibility data surfaces in the Agent Prompt Guide (Quick Color Reference plus any flagged focus/contrast problems) rather than a numbered §9; absent a11y data is noted honestly rather than fabricated. The underlying capture mechanics (`a11y-extract.ts` populating `tokens.accessibility`) are unchanged.\n\n  Line 399: - Objective: confirm the v3 Style Reference mirrors a11y-extract.ts output faithfully, never inventing values\n\n  Line 404: | A11Y-001 | Accessibility section fidelity | Verify the v3 Style Reference's Agent Prompt Guide mirrors a11y-extract.ts output, never invents values, and honestly notes absence | `Does the design system capture accessibility data?` | 1. verify both tokens.json and the Style Reference exist -> 2. `node -e \"...` inspect accessibility fields from tokens.json -> 3. agent reads the Agent Prompt Guide and any flagged a11y notes -> 4. agent compares field-by-field | Step 1: tokens.json and the Style Reference present. Step 2: node script prints a11y field counts (or NO_ACCESSIBILITY_OBJECT). Step 3: the Style Reference contains either populated a11y data or an explicit absence note. Step 4: every reported a11y value traces to a field in tokens.json | Node inspect output of tokens.json accessibility fields, Style Reference a11y text excerpt, field-by-field comparison table | PASS if the Style Reference faithfully mirrors tokens.json accessibility data (populated when present, honest absence note when absent) with zero invented values. FAIL if it contains a11y values not in tokens.json OR omits a11y data that tokens.json contains OR is missing entirely when a11y data exists | 1. If accessibility object is missing from tokens.json, confirm `extract.ts` calls `extractA11y()` during Phase 1 (contrast + focus + touch-target + ARIA stats from DOM collections). 2. If tabOrder/langAttribute/skipLinkDetected/altTextCoverage are missing, confirm `extract.ts` calls `extractA11yAsync(page)` which runs Playwright page-dependent checks. 3. If the a11y data is missing from the Style Reference, verify the WRITE phase loaded `SKILL.md` §4 ALWAYS rule 7 and the v3 format spec (`references/design_md_format.md`). 4. If the a11y prose fabricates data, rerun the write phase with explicit instruction \"every a11y value must come from tokens.json verbatim.\" |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/04--convergence-and-recovery/stuck-recovery-widens-focus-and-continues.md:\n  Line 50: 3. `bash: rg -n 'RECOVERY MODE|research-ideas|Exhausted Approaches' .opencode/agents/deep-research.toml`\n\n  Line 78: | `.opencode/agents/deep-research.toml` | Runtime recovery behavior; inspect `Recovery Mode` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/context_loading_contract.md:\n  Line 257:   mirrored arrows/chevrons: pass | fail | N/A\n\n  Line 258:   non-mirrored exceptions:\n\n  Line 262: Use logical properties for RTL-sensitive layout (`margin-inline-start`, `padding-inline-start`, `text-align: start`) and mirror directional icons such as arrows and chevrons. Do not mirror logos, clocks, media-play controls, or other symbols whose direction has semantic meaning. This lane is hybrid: field presence is convention-enforced for global surfaces, while expansion quality and icon judgment remain advisory.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/README.md:\n  Line 135: | Runtime mirror behaves differently across CLI executors | Provider quirks or missing capabilities | Compare the mirror against `references/guides/capability_matrix.md` and `assets/runtime_capabilities.json` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/changelog/v0.1.0.md:\n  Line 24: - Change: `skill_graph_scan`, `skill_graph_query`, `skill_graph_status` and `skill_graph_validate` expose the package-local SQLite graph. Lifecycle, freshness and trust state mirror the advisor tools.\n\n  Line 40: - Change: `skill_advisor.py` probes the native advisor first and translates the response back to the legacy JSON-array shape. If the native probe is unavailable, it falls back to the local Python scorer. `--force-native` and `--force-local` testing toggles ship for rollback debugging. The OpenCode plugin bridge mirrors the same fail-open pattern.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/05--context-report-synthesis/reduce-state-merge.md:\n  Line 87: - [cross-executor-agreement.md](../03--agreement-merge/cross-executor-agreement.md) — The agreement logic the reducer mirrors\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/03--agreement-merge/finding-dedup-by-symbol.md:\n  Line 42: `fanout-merge.cjs` provides the canonical per-executor attribution shape. `step_merge_findings` reuses this shape (or mirrors it exactly) so the findings registry stays consistent with the runtime contract whether the host merges inline or delegates to the fanout-merge script.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/06--synthesis-save-and-guardrails/final-synthesis-memory-save-and-guardrail-behavior.md:\n  Line 49: 2. `bash: rg -n 'LEAF-only|Task tool|NEVER create sub-tasks|reference-only|Wave orchestration|Checkpoint Commit|Direct Mode Fallback|Segment Model' .opencode/agents/deep-research.toml .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/references/state/state_format.md`\n\n  Line 77: | `.opencode/agents/deep-research.toml` | Canonical runtime guardrails; inspect `## 0. ILLEGAL NESTING (HARD BLOCK)` and `SPEC FOLDER PERMISSION` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/feature_catalog/02--state-management/config-management.md:\n  Line 21: Config management keeps the packet honest about what may change during the loop and what must stay fixed. It is also where runtime-specific mirrors are described without changing the core packet shape.\n\n  Line 29: The config also points at the runtime capability matrix and resolver script. `runtime_capabilities.json` lists the OpenCode, Claude, and OpenCode mirrors with their tool surfaces, hook behavior, and schema-adaptation notes. `runtime-capabilities.cjs` loads and validates that machine-readable matrix so the runtime documentation stays synchronized with the same capability source.\n\n  Line 41: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/assets/runtime_capabilities.json` | Asset | Defines the machine-readable runtime capability matrix for supported mirrors. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/07--runtime-robustness/post-dispatch-validate.md:\n  Line 23: This mirrors the runtime `post-dispatch-validate` discipline applied in the mature deep-loop runtime for iteration-level outputs, adapted for context-loop seat findings.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/08--council-graph-integration/council-graph-tools-registered-separately-from-deep-loop.md:\n  Line 85: | `feature_catalog/` | Feature catalog mirror |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/07--runtime-robustness/atomic-state.md:\n  Line 35: When the TypeScript toolchain is unavailable, `loadStateSafety` falls back to `writeStateAtomicInline`, which mirrors the runtime contract using Node.js `fs` calls directly: write to a `.tmp.<pid>.<ts>.<random>` path, then `fs.renameSync` onto the target. The dashboard always goes through `writeTextAtomic` (the inline equivalent for text files).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/06--depth-and-failure-handling/depth-detection-parallel-vs-sequential.md:\n  Line 31: - Expected signals: Agent body contains Depth 0, Depth 1, and `sequential_thinking` rules; `depth_dispatch.md` mirrors the numbered sections and decision rule.\n\n  Line 33: - Pass/fail: PASS if detection rules are present in the agent body and mirrored in `depth_dispatch.md`; FAIL if either source is missing the rule.\n\n  Line 64: - **Pass**: Detection rules present in agent body and mirrored in `depth_dispatch.md`.\n\n  Line 65: - **Fail**: Depth 1 is absent, `sequential_thinking` is absent, or the reference does not mirror source behavior.\n\n  Line 91: | `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/convergence/depth_dispatch.md` | Reference mirror for operator use |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/03--iteration-execution-and-state-discipline/strategy-next-focus-and-exhausted-approach-discipline.md:\n  Line 49: 2. `bash: rg -n 'Exhausted Approaches|MANDATORY PRE-CHECK|RECOVERY' .opencode/agents/deep-research.toml`\n\n  Line 76: | `.opencode/agents/deep-research.toml` | Exhausted-approach discipline and focus selection; inspect `Step 2: Determine Focus` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:\n  Line 168: `step_merge_findings` computes `unit_id = sha256(path:symbol:kind)` for each finding, groups all findings across surviving seats by unit_id, unions per-executor attribution into `producedBy` (distinct seat labels), derives `agreement = count(distinct executors in producedBy)`, and marks units as agreement-eligible when `agreement >= config.agreementMin` (default 2). `fanout-merge.cjs` provides the canonical attribution shape; the host reuses it or mirrors its shape to keep the registry consistent with the runtime contract.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/02--council-deliberation-and-seat-diversity/three-seat-diverse-deliberation.md:\n  Line 67: Check the reference first, then the agent strategy section, then runtime mirrors if parity is suspect.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/manual_testing_playbook/10--accessibility/accessibility-section.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Validates the accessibility data in the v3 Style Reference mirrors the a11y data captured by a11y-extract.ts, with honest absence-notation when no a11y data exists. Tests that the Style Reference's Agent Prompt Guide and any flagged a11y problems reflect measured contrast ratios, focus indicators, and touch-target sizes without fabrication.\"\n\n  Line 50: - Objective: confirm the v3 Style Reference's a11y data mirrors a11y-extract.ts output faithfully, never inventing values\n\n  Line 54: - Expected signals: `tokens.json` either has a populated `accessibility` object (with at least `contrastPairs` and `focusIndicator`) OR has no `accessibility` key; the async fields (`langAttribute`, `skipLinkDetected`, `tabOrder`, `altTextCoverage`, `reducedMotionSupport`) are populated when the async pass captured them; `focusIndicator.captured` reflects whether focus styles were actually captured; the Style Reference mirrors whatever the tokens contain, using \"Not captured\" or \"No data available\" language when fields are absent, and never asserts focus indicators are \"consistent\" when `focusIndicator.captured` is false\n\n  Line 80: | A11Y-001 | Accessibility section fidelity | Verify the v3 Style Reference's a11y data mirrors a11y-extract.ts output, never invents values, and honestly notes absence | `Does the design system capture accessibility data?` | 1. verify both tokens.json and the Style Reference exist -> 2. `node -e \"...` inspect accessibility fields from tokens.json -> 3. agent reads the Style Reference's a11y data -> 4. agent compares field-by-field | Step 1: tokens.json and the Style Reference present. Step 2: node script prints a11y field counts (or NO_ACCESSIBILITY_OBJECT). Step 3: the Style Reference contains either populated a11y data or an explicit absence note. Step 4: every reported a11y value traces to a field in tokens.json | Node inspect output of tokens.json accessibility fields, Style Reference a11y text excerpt, field-by-field comparison table | PASS if the Style Reference faithfully mirrors tokens.json accessibility data (populated when present, honest absence note when absent) with zero invented values. FAIL if it contains a11y values not in tokens.json OR omits a11y data that tokens.json contains OR is missing entirely when a11y data exists | 1. If accessibility object is missing from tokens.json, confirm `extract.ts` calls `extractA11y()` during Phase 1 (contrast + focus + touch-target + ARIA stats from DOM