 at least 3 distinct agent slugs from the documented roster (general, context, review, write, debug, deep-research, deep-review, ai-council, deep-improvement). Steps are sequenced (Step 1, Step 2, etc.) with handoff descriptions. Zero `opencode run` nested invocations in tool.call payloads. Dispatched command line includes `--agent orchestrate`.\n\n  Line 50: | CO-034 | Orchestrate agent multi-agent coordination | Verify --agent orchestrate produces a sequenced multi-agent plan with no nested opencode run dispatches | `As an external-AI conductor facing a complex task that requires multiple OpenCode specializations in sequence, dispatch opencode run --agent orchestrate --variant high --format json --dir <repo-root> \"Plan a comprehensive audit of the cli-opencode skill itself. Decompose into a sequence of OpenCode specialist agents (e.g., context, review, write, ai-council) with explicit handoffs between steps. Name each agent slug, the artifact each step produces, and what it hands to the next step. Do not dispatch nested opencode run invocations.\" Verify the response names at least 3 distinct agent slugs in sequence with handoffs and that zero nested opencode-run tool.calls appear. Return a verdict naming the agents in planned order and confirming the no-nested-run constraint.` | 1. `bash: rm -rf /tmp/co-034-events.jsonl && git status --porcelain > /tmp/co-034-pre.txt` -> 2. `opencode run --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --agent orchestrate --variant high --format json --dir \"$(pwd)\" \"Plan a comprehensive audit of the cli-opencode skill itself. Decompose into a sequence of OpenCode specialist agents (for example context, review, write, ai-council) with explicit handoffs between steps. Name each agent slug, the artifact each step produces, and what it hands to the next step. Do not dispatch nested opencode run invocations.\" > /tmp/co-034-events.jsonl 2>&1` -> 3. `bash: echo \"Exit: $?\"` -> 4. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"session.completed\") \\| .payload.summary // empty' /tmp/co-034-events.jsonl > /tmp/co-034-summary.txt` -> 5. `bash: grep -ciE '(general\\|context\\|review\\|write\\|debug\\|deep-research\\|deep-review\\|ai-council\\|deep-improvement)' /tmp/co-034-summary.txt` -> 6. `bash: grep -ciE '(step [0-9]+\\|handoff\\|hand off\\|hands to\\|passes to)' /tmp/co-034-summary.txt` -> 7. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"tool.call\") \\|...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/multi-ai-council-multi-strategy.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates the ai-council planning-only agent for `CO-017`. It focuses on confirming `--agent ai-council` produces multiple distinct strategies scored across a rubric and respects the planning-only constraint (no file modifications).\"\n\n  Line 15: This scenario validates the Ultra-think multi-strategy planning agent for `CO-017`. It focuses on confirming `--agent ai-council` generates at least 3 distinct solution strategies, scores each across a multi-dimension rubric, recommends one with rationale, AND respects the planning-only constraint documented in `references/agent_delegation.md` §7 (no file modifications).\n\n  Line 19: `ai-council` is the canonical multi-strategy planning architect. Its value depends on two contracts: produce diverse, well-scored strategies (not a single linear plan). Never write files (planning-only LEAF constraint). If either contract breaks, the agent loses its differentiator from `general` and its safety story for use in pre-implementation planning. This test validates both contracts simultaneously.\n\n  Line 27: - Objective: Confirm `--agent ai-council` produces at least 3 distinct strategies scored on at least 3 dimensions with an explicit recommendation, AND no file modifications occur.\n\n  Line 28: - Real user request: `Use opencode run with --agent ai-council to compare 3 strategies for migrating a small JS module from CommonJS to ESM. Confirm the response has 3 strategies, each scored on at least 3 dimensions, an explicit recommendation, AND no files were modified.`\n\n  Line 29: - RCAF Prompt: `As an external-AI conductor planning a CommonJS-to-ESM migration of a single hypothetical module, dispatch --agent ai-council to compare three strategies (big-bang rewrite, incremental wrapper, dual-build). Verify the response presents three distinct strategies, scores each across risk/effort/timeline/reversibility, recommends one with rationale, and does NOT modify any files in the repo. Return a concise pass/fail verdict naming the recommended strategy and the dimension count per strategy.`\n\n  Line 30: - Expected execution process: External-AI orchestrator snapshots a few sentinel file mtimes, dispatches with `--agent ai-council`, validates the response presents three distinct strategies with scoring across at least three dimensions and an explicit recommendation and confirms the sentinel mtimes are unchanged.\n\n  Line 43: 3. Dispatch with `--agent ai-council` and the multi-strategy planning prompt.\n\n  Line 51: | CO-017 | Ultra-think multi-strategy planning | Confirm `--agent ai-council` produces 3+ distinct strategies scored across 3+ dimensions with no file writes | `As an external-AI conductor planning a CommonJS-to-ESM migration of a single hypothetical module, dispatch --agent ai-council to compare three strategies (big-bang rewrite, incremental wrapper, dual-build). Verify the response presents three distinct strategies, scores each across risk/effort/timeline/reversibility, recommends one with rationale, and does NOT modify any files in the repo. Return a concise pass/fail verdict naming the recommended strategy and the dimension count per strategy.` | 1. `bash: stat -f '%m %N' .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md > /tmp/co-017-mtimes-before.txt && cat /tmp/co-017-mtimes-before.txt` -> 2. `bash: opencode run --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --agent ai-council --variant high --format json --dir \"$(pwd)\" \"Compare three strategies for migrating a single CommonJS Node module to ESM: (1) big-bang rewrite, (2) incremental wrapper, (3) dual-build. Score each across risk, effort, timeline, and reversibility. Recommend one with rationale. PLANNING-ONLY — do not modify any files.\" > /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl 2>&1` -> 3. `bash: echo \"Exit: $?\"` -> 4. `bash: stat -f '%m %N' .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md > /tmp/co-017-mtimes-after.txt && diff /tmp/co-017-mtimes-before.txt /tmp/co-017-mtimes-after.txt && echo SENTINEL_MTIMES_OK` -> 5. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"tool.call\") \\| .payload.name' /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl \\| grep -ciE '(Edit\\|Write)'` -> 6. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"message.delta\" or .type == \"session.completed\") \\| .payload' /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl \\| grep -ciE '(big-bang\\|incremental wrapper\\|dual-build)'` -> 7. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"message.delta\" or .type == \"session.completed\") \\| .payload' /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl \\| grep...\n  Line 55: For rubric depth, ask the agent to produce a 5x5 markdown table with strategies as rows and dimensions as columns. Confirm every cell has a non-empty score. This is the \"ideal output shape\" for ai-council dispatches and stresses the agent's ability to produce structured output.\n\n  Line 66: | `../../references/agent_delegation.md` (§3 ai-council property table + §7 LEAF constraints) | Ultra-think planning-only contract |\n\n  Line 72: | `../../SKILL.md` | §3 agent routing table (`ai-council` row) |\n\n  Line 73: | `../../assets/prompt_templates.md` (TEMPLATE 10: Multi-strategy planning via @MULTI-AI COUNCIL) | Canonical ai-council prompt shape |\n\n  Line 82: - Feature file path: `04--agent-routing/005-ai-council-multi-strategy.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/changelog/v0.3.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release lands the system-skill-advisor portion of the packets 108 plus 110 auto-review uplift program. Four reusable teachings from the upstream `dzianisv/opencode-plugins` auto-review package now apply to both the skill internals and the `mk-skill-advisor.js` plugin: async file I/O with a closure-scoped lazy-mkdir guard, opt-in debug logging, a 4-tier configuration precedence and awaited config loading at module init. Every mechanism cleared a 5-of-5 unanimous deep-ai-council review by `cli-codex gpt-5.5 xhigh fast` before any code shipped and the council reshaped the H-3 plus H-6 scope in a load-bearing way: the disk writes had to remain AWAITED rather than fire-and-forget so the bounded-retention contract for metrics records survives.\n\n  Line 35: Both packets ran through a 5-seat deep-ai-council deliberation before any source change. The council returned REQUEST-CHANGES on the first pass with HIGH confidence and reshaped scope on three load-bearing points. First, the `metrics.ts` writes had to remain awaited so the bounded-retention read-then-rewrite-last-N pattern survives. Second, the plugin factory had to await the config promise before normalizing options. Third, the existing env-var disable handling at lines 35 through 39 had to be preserved unchanged so the disable surface remained stable. Implementation followed via `cli-opencode + deepseek-v4-pro --pure`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/changelog/v1.3.0.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release lands the sk-code-review portion of the packets 108 plus 110 auto-review uplift program, applying 5 reusable teachings (H-1, H-2, H-4, M-1, M-2) distilled from a deep-research pass over the upstream `dzianisv/opencode-plugins` auto-review package. Every mechanism cleared a 5-of-5 unanimous deep-ai-council review by `cli-codex gpt-5.5 xhigh fast` before any code shipped, which caught real bugs and reshaped scope. The net effect is a review surface that emits a parseable verdict on its final line, refuses to repeat findings across iterations, and can short-circuit on already-reviewed pull-request state or low-evidence diffs without ever skipping security, authentication, configuration, persistence, dependency, sandbox, or public-facing changes.\n\n  Line 43: Both packets ran through a 5-seat deep-ai-council deliberation before any source change. The council was dispatched via `cli-codex gpt-5.5 xhigh fast` and returned REQUEST-CHANGES on the first pass for each packet with HIGH confidence. The revisions that landed in this release include: H-1 rendered as plain text rather than Markdown bold; H-2 markers placed at the dispatcher boundary rather than inside frontmatter-bearing reference templates; M-2 skip taxonomy expanded to cover seven sensitive change classes that must never short-circuit. Implementation followed via `cli-opencode + deepseek-v4-pro --pure`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/README.md:\n  Line 76: You get structured JSON events streamed to stdout as the session runs, ending with a final tool-result message. The `</dev/null` is mandatory on non-interactive runs. Do not pass top-level `--agent` by default: `context`, `review` and `debug` are subagents that route through a primary/orchestrate path, and direct top-level `--agent` use is only conditionally allowed for primary agents such as `plan`, `orchestrate` or `ai-council` after `opencode run --help` confirms acceptance.\n\n  Line 164: | `--agent general` fails or warns | The default/general path is selected by omitting `--agent` | Omit `--agent general`; use `orchestrate` or `ai-council` only when they are the documented primary route and help-verified. Route `context`, `review` and `debug` through the documented primary/Task path instead of direct top-level `--agent` examples. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/agent_delegation.md:\n  Line 133: | `ai-council` | Multi-strategy planning architect | Complex planning that benefits from comparing multiple solution strategies. PLANNING-ONLY |\n\n  Line 186: ### @ai-council — Multi-Strategy Planning Architect\n\n  Line 197: **Command-only (as of `mode: subagent`).** Direct `opencode run --agent ai-council` is no longer reachable — `ai-council.md` is `mode: subagent`, not directly selectable as a top-level session agent. Dispatch via `/deep:ai-council` for a full session, or via `opencode run --agent general \"...\"` and let `general`/`orchestrate`'s own routing Task-dispatch to `@ai-council` for a single planning pass.\n\n  Line 229: | Multi-strategy planning | `ai-council` | **Command-only.** Dispatch via `/deep:ai-council` for a full session, or `opencode run --agent general --variant high --format json --dir /repo \"Plan the authentication redesign — compare three strategies.\"` and let orchestrate's routing Task-dispatch `@ai-council`. Direct `opencode run --agent ai-council` is forbidden as of `mode: subagent`. |\n\n  Line 299: | `ai-council` | PLANNING-ONLY — no file modifications |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/opencode_tools.md:\n  Line 139: The `--agent <slug>` flag loads an agent definition from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md`. The frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, and system prompt. Specialized agents (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `context`, `review`, `ai-council`, etc.) provide domain-specific behavior the calling AI can target.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md:\n  Line 293: | `ai-council` | Multi-strategy planning |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/SKILL.md:\n  Line 38: - Strategy deliberation between competing plans — use `deep-ai-council`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release lands the system-code-graph portion of the packets 108 plus 110 auto-review uplift program. Four reusable teachings from the upstream `dzianisv/opencode-plugins` auto-review package now apply to both the skill internals and the `mk-code-graph.js` plugin: async file I/O with a closure-scoped lazy-mkdir guard in the user-facing feedback handler, a 4-tier configuration precedence in the plugin, and awaited config loading at module init. The most load-bearing council ruling for this release is that `ccc-feedback.ts` writes must remain AWAITED rather than fire-and-forget — the MCP error-return contract at lines 64 through 72 depends on the disk write completing before the handler returns its result envelope. Every mechanism cleared a 5-of-5 unanimous deep-ai-council review by `cli-codex gpt-5.5 xhigh fast` before any code shipped.\n\n  Line 35: Both packets ran through a 5-seat deep-ai-council deliberation before any source change. The council returned REQUEST-CHANGES on the first pass with HIGH confidence and reshaped scope on three load-bearing points for this skill. First, `ccc-feedback.ts` writes had to remain awaited to preserve the MCP error-return contract — this is the single most important safeguard in this release. Second, no debug-enable gate was applied to `ccc-feedback.ts` because user-facing feedback persistence must always run. Third, the plugin factory had to await the config promise before normalizing options. Implementation followed via `cli-opencode + deepseek-v4-pro --pure`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 15: cli-opencode previously documented 9 agents as `--agent`-invokable, but only 4 are actually primary (directly callable). The `general` and `plan` agents are OpenCode built-ins; `orchestrate` is mode=primary; `multi-ai-council` is mode=all. The other 8 (`context`, `debug`, `review`, `write`, `deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-agent-improvement`, `prompt-improver`) are mode=subagent and dispatch via Task tool from a primary. SKILL.md §3 now splits into two tables — primary agents (directly invokable) and subagents (routed via `--agent orchestrate \"Use the X subagent to ...\"`).\n\n  Line 23: Scenarios CO-014 (context), CO-015 (review), CO-016 (write), CO-032 (deep-research), CO-033 (deep-review) previously dispatched `--agent <subagent>` directly, which opencode rejects with a \"agent X is a subagent, not a primary agent. Falling back to default agent\" warning. Each scenario's TEST EXECUTION bash command now dispatches via `--agent orchestrate` with a `\"Use the <subagent> subagent to ...\"` prompt prefix. CO-013 (general), CO-017 (multi-ai-council), CO-034 (orchestrate) were already correctly using primaries.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/skill_benchmark/fixtures/deep-loop-workflows/routing-precision.md:\n  Line 26: | multi-seat deliberation | `deep-loop-workflows`, `ai-council` |\n\n  Line 31: review, ai-council) are scored by this probe. `dlw-context-001` (context =\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/workflows/quick_reference.md:\n  Line 113: - `/deep:ai-council` - run multi-seat planning deliberation\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.4.1.0.md:\n  Line 31: | Multi-AI Council scoped-write | **`artifact_written` event append ≤ 5 ms; round-NNN rollback ≤ 100 ms** | Council writes its own artifact tree under `ai-council/**`. Audit trail and rollback are first-class. |\n\n  Line 70: | **Multi-AI Council** | Full output-protocol contract shipped. v1.1 state metadata. Scoped-write, council writes its own `ai-council/**` artifacts. Advisory completion checker. |\n\n  Line 301: The Multi-AI Council agent now ships a complete output protocol contract instead of an implicit one. Agent body §12 through §17 document the output protocol, invocation contract, state schema, convergence signal, caller-persistence protocol, and summary. Four shared reference files under `system-spec-kit/references/ai-council/` cover folder layout, seat diversity patterns, convergence signals, and JSONL state format.\n\n  Line 305: The validator regression test confirms the new `ai-council/` artifact folder pattern is tolerated. Three-runtime mirror parity tests prevent the agent body from drifting between Claude, Codex, and OpenCode definitions.\n\n  Line 309: The council writes its own artifact tree. Permission across the three runtime mirrors: `write: allow / edit: allow`; `bash: deny / patch: deny`. Path-scope to `ai-council/**` is enforced by the writer library, `scripts/ai-council/lib/persist-artifacts.js` throws `OUT_OF_SCOPE_WRITE` for any out-of-bounds target. The audit-trail schema is additive v1.1 → v1.2 with new `artifact_written` and `rollback` event types; v1 readers continue to parse v1.2 files unchanged. Round-NNN folder is the rollback unit; on seat error or convergence failure, the round artifacts move to `failed/round-NNN-<timestamp>/` and the audit trail records `superseded_by: \"rollback\"` markers. Three ADRs (write-permission model, audit-trail schema, rollback semantics) document the decisions. 7 new vitest cases cover permission-scope, runtime-parity, audit-trail, and rollback.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/README.md:\n  Line 113: Skip it for a single-pass lookup, where the `@context` agent is faster. Skip it for outward web research (use `deep-research`), code audits (`deep-review`) or strategy comparison (`deep-ai-council`).\n\n  Line 117: `deep-context` shares the `deep-loop-runtime` through the `deep-loop-workflows` roster: context, research, review, ai-council, and improvement. Each owns a different phase of the planning-to-implementation pipeline and none crosses into another's territory. The improvement persona exposes four public command/workflow lanes: `agent-improvement`, `model-benchmark`, `skill-benchmark`, and `ai-system-improvement`; `non-dev-ai-system-refine` is the loop-host mode for the Lane D adapter.\n\n  Line 123: | `deep-ai-council` | Compares competing plans with structured disagreement. Run `deep-context` first so seats start from shared facts. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/workflows/agent-io-contract.md:\n  Line 42: agent: @orchestrate | @context | @code | @review | @debug | @markdown | @prompt-improver | @ai-council | @deep-context | @deep-research | @deep-review | @deep-improvement\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.6.0.0.md:\n  Line 19: | **One hub for the deep loops** | The five deep skills (context, research, review, ai-council, improvement) run as a single hub over a shared backend. Every `/deep:*` command and agent name is unchanged. |\n\n  Line 163: The five public identities (context, research, review, ai-council and improvement) now live in one hub that sits over a shared, frozen backend. The hub holds no per-mode logic of its own. It reads which mode you want and routes to it, and each mode keeps its own behavior. Advisor routing collapsed five skill identities into one plus a mode alias, and the old five-skill surface is gone. The change is invisible where it counts: every `/deep:*` command and every agent name is unchanged, and the only thing you might notice is that diagnostics now check both of the loop's databases instead of missing one.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/README.md:\n  Line 12: Shared domain logic for the `deep-loop-workflows` hub, which routes context, research, review, ai-council, and four improvement lanes. Graph-backed workflow modes use `runtimeLoopType` values `research`, `review`, `council`, or `context`; improvement lanes keep `runtimeLoopType: null`. Each subdomain isolates its own concerns. This is the domain layer; CLI-specific infrastructure lives in `scripts/lib/` instead.\n\n  Line 18: | `council/` | Multi-seat dispatch, adjudicator-verdict scoring, cost guards | ai-council workflow packets |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/council/README.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Multi-seat dispatch, adjudicator-verdict stability, and cost guards for deep-ai-council deep mode.\"\n\n  Line 12: Runtime primitives consumed by deep-ai-council orchestrators for iterative multi-topic deliberation. Implements 3-level state hierarchy (session to topic to round) with verdict-delta convergence scoring.\n\n  Line 29: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs`\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"ai-council|deep-ai-council","time":{"start":1782919041510,"end":1782919041590}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_052b73d6d7448eb4016a452f7faf9c8191b6c0dd7ff4866661"}},"id":"prt_f1e4191ce001d2R2GE1K587vDW","sessionID":"ses_0e1c12f14ffe56Cs01FOXHPL99","messageID":"msg_f1e412e42001e7STSMZLmXs9fI"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782919042255,"sessionID":"ses_0e1c12f14ffe56Cs01FOXHPL99","part":{"id":"prt_f1e4194c9001nvcahIDv13g0RI","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"6d9a7e5dacbf04e2a0140385843ff24f912f6687","messageID":"msg_f1e412e42001e7STSMZLmXs9fI","sessionID":"ses_0e1c12f14ffe56Cs01FOXHPL99","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":71270,"input":5221,"output":382,"reasoning":131,"cache":{"write":0,"read":65536}},"cost":0}}
